I think that with increased air travel and rising global temperatures the air temperature in Dubai will be slightly above 35.5 degrees, such as in 2020. However, I gave myself a buffer as this number can be attributed to a variety of factors.

I made my predictions by looking at the Dubai International Airport Temperature History for this year. The temperature peaked between May and August and is starting to decrease. Although it was hotter during these months (38-43 degrees Celsius), towards the beginning of the year the temperatures ranged from 15-37 degrees Celsius. Additionally it is predicted that the average temperature will remain between 35-36 degrees Celsius until the end of the year. After looking at this data, I believe that the temperature will average around 35.5-36.5 degrees Celsius.

Ran conditional regression 2 ways, once with the summer average vs Sept values and another with Summer as a function of May, June, July, Aug, and Sept. I'm coming up with a final summer average of approximately 35.17 deg C +/- about 0.1 degree based on the RMSE residuals. Finally I created a Haywood Plot of the average from May until now. The plot is converging on just a little above 35 deg C, so I feel pretty good that my results from LinReg and Haywood plotting are in agreement. Am upping my bet for bin 2 as a consequence given the short remaining time.

Adjusting bets as I watch the data. After graphing out multiple years and averaging them, the peak summer average typically occur between days 120 and 140 after May 1st. Too bad we can't show graphs or analysis results here! So far, still betting the most on Bin2.

The early "negative temperature anomaly" seen at the beginning of the Question period hasn't quite burned off with time, even though well beyond 50% of the Question time period has now elapsed. However, the anomaly calculated over the longer timeframe we have now (May-late July) is now much less than -1C. This is largely because of warmer-than-average days in late June, but for what it's worth, I've also noticed some upward revision of the early June temperature data as reported now vs my download at the time of my last "check-in". On average, we've seen daily temps -0.43C lower than the corresponding daily averages calculated over the 2014-2021 timeframe. For reference, the May-September average across these years (8 years x 153 days each) was ~35.49C, and if the second half of our time period maintains a statistical temperature anomaly similar to what we've seen so far, then we're basically on track for a mid-bin #2 outcome. We'd need to see an average going-forward temperature anomaly > +0.5C vs previous years to have any chance of bin #3. Climate model forecasts continue to suggest that this is much less likely than not to actually happen. Presumably, as forecasting time windows get shorter, these predictions should become increasingly accurate as well.

Am running OLS estimates of the final average summer temperature vs cumulative summer month averages. I don't typically like ending up this far from the crowd judgment, but my ensemble estimates point more to Bin 2 than Bin 3 - even after aggregating with selected peers. For now I am trusting the math and hoping I don't get crushed in the end.

I've gone through the data in more detail and evaluated the averages across months and years. My analysis suggests that @MCowley has made a very good observation. If you regress the cumulative monthly averages against the summer average, it becomes apparent that low temps (especially in June and July), will pull the summer average down. Since the cumulative averages determine the summer average, the linear relationship is not surprising. After aggregating with selected crowd, I am modifying my forecast accordingly by upping my Bin 2 probability.
Slight modification, based on comments and thinking from @MCowley. I will go look at the data myself when I get a chance, but am moderating my bets slightly based on this.

Just starting out. I used the obvious trend to extrapolate the summer average forward, and aggregated with a Holt Winters and ARMA(1,1) forecast + crowd.

In addition to the surprisingly large negative temperature anomaly we've been seeing so far (on avg., we've seen daily temps. this year -1.26C lower than the corresponding daily avg. over the 2014-2021 timeframe, with ~27% of Question period elapsed), the updated models for this year are pointing at bin #2 as well. If you look closely at the models linked in a previous forecast, you see a tiny region of lower temps right over Dubai, even though higher-than-normal temps are modeled for the vast majority of the Arabian peninsula. Wish I'd noticed that sooner! That being said, there's always a significant random component to weather, and it's still credible to me that we'll see some anomalously hot days balancing out the "colder" days seen so far, so that we *barely* end up in bin #3 by end of Question.

Great question, and with a meteorology background I feel inclined to forecast (and probably get wrong).

From 2014 to 2021, the year-by-year average temperatures over the timeframe of interest (Meteostat) were: [34.63 35.68 35.38 35.91 35.55 35.63 35.49 35.64], suggesting a "literal" ballpark ~37% chance of bin #2, and 63% chance of bin #3, if 2022 is like the recent past. Incorporating more or fewer years will of course change the estimated probabilities somewhat.

Historically reviewed last 50 years of weather data to demonstrate potential offering. Likelihood of a temperature less than 34.5 degrees Celsiuis not deemed statistically significant. 20-25% of the year includes temperature ranges between 34.5 and 35.5 degrees with the preponderance of temperatures rangig between 35.5-36.5 degrees.

May to September are the hottest months of the year. However, they are also the cloudiest months of the year. Increases in temperature that have been trending in recent years may disrupt the upward trend from year to year. Forecasting cloud cover over 6 months from now is dubious, so it may only decrease the likelihood of a significant jump in average temps. Given the few years that I initially looked at, the trend is minimal but appears to be above 35.5. Revisiting this question to look at other time periods will help refine forecasting percentages.

Initial forecast loosely references Meteostat base rates, but is tweaked to reflect somewhat less confidence in the “preferred” bins suggested by past outcomes. This reflects a slightly increased chance of significant up- or downward y-o-y deviation from historical trends caused by “Global Weirding” climate change (vs a forecast that more directly reproduces historical patterns).

Using data from the last 10 years there is a mean temperature of 35.3 degrees. There is a small upward trend of average temperature over this period, with a linear regression giving a predicted temperature of 35.5 degrees. The SD of the data over this period is approximately 0.5 degrees, so +/- 1 degree represents 2 SD from the mean, assuming a normal distribution.

I expect a base case of slight warming (+0.1), but I don't expect an average temperature taken over 5 months to change drastically (+2 degrees C) based on historical trends. However, climate change also means more frequent and extreme weather events, so I'm weighting nearby buckets a tiny bit. Such events would have to be either fairly large or fairly long-lasting to move a 5-month average substantially.
